  "final_answer": "Using the proxy of high stress as low satisfaction and/or slight grade decline, there are 11 students who appear to have relatively high stress despite low daily usage of AI tools (<= 1.8 hours).\n\nWho they are:\n- Student IDs: 1, 3, 24, 30, 38, 41, 43, 57, 65, 79, 86\n\nWhat stands out:\n- Low satisfaction is the strongest signal:\n  - 8 of 11 had Low satisfaction\n- Academic outcomes were not strongly positive:\n  - 4 had Slight Decline in grades\n  - 4 had No Change\n  - 3 had Improved grades\n- Most common usage purposes:\n  - Writing: 4\n  - Research: 2\n  - Learning: 2\n  - Coding: 2\n  - Homework: 1\n\nPossible factors that might explain the stress:\n- Dissatisfaction with AI support seems important, since most of these students reported Low satisfaction.\n- Limited academic payoff may be contributing:\n  - Most students saw either no improvement or a slight decline in grades.\n- Writing-related use appears most common, which may suggest students are using AI for assignment pressure rather than deeper learning support.\n- The group is concentrated more in:\n  - School level: 6 students\n  - College level: 4 students\n- Tool use is spread across several platforms, but Gemini and ChatGPT appear most often:\n  - Gemini: 4\n  - ChatGPT: 3\n\nImportant caveat:\n- The dataset does not include a direct stress variable, so this is an inferred group rather than confirmed high-stress students.",
